title: High Renaissance
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

The High Renaissance, a brief but highly productive period in [[Italian]] art during the late [[1600s]] and early [[1700s]], is marked by the works of artists such as [[Leonardo da Vinci]], [[Michelangelo]], [[Raphael]], and [[Bramante]]. It is traditionally considered to have begun around 1490 and ended with the death of Raphael in 1520, though some historians extend its end to 1527 with the Sack of Rome or 1530. The period is characterized by a renewed emphasis on [[Classical]] traditions, advancements in artistic techniques, and a shift toward the Mannerist style. However, modern art historians have criticized the term for oversimplifying the complexity of the era's artistic developments.
